	   <tr><td colspan=2>Re: Duel wield.&nbsp;&nbsp;Sorry bud.  Im not sure that is correct.  The performance of your offhand weapon has nothing to do with what is in your primary hand.  You can stick a lantern in your primary hand, a stein of moggok, a jade mace, a torch, a fine steel long sword--it doesn't matter one bit. You will still get (substantially) the same performance from your offhand.<br><br>If you want independent corraboration, try asking the question at the safehouse, ranger's glade, or monkly business. Or just do your own testing.<br><br>To test this, grab a mid-level bard (mid level needed so he has a decent dual wield chance). Bards are a better test case because they only have one random factor (dual wield chance) versus two for monks, rogues, warriors rangers (duel wield and double attack). Put a fast piercer in the bard's offhand and a slow one hand slash (like a fine steel long sword). Duel the bard and stand there, logging the number piercing attempts (you'll need others hits and misses on) over, say, 3 minutes. Now have the bard put a jade mace in their primary hand and repeat the logging process.<br><br>You'll find the number of piercing attempts in both cases (slow one hand slash in primary, fast one hand blunt in primary) to be statistically equivalent. There will be some variation, but it's due solely to dual wield being a probabilistic action.<br><br>Re: agro--Last nite in KC I was grouping with a 45 WAR (with my 55SK).  You are absolutely correct about a lower level having a easier time getting agro, because I had a hell of a time keeping agro on me (I was forced to cast high taunt spells, which worked, but it wasnt easy).<br><br>Re: Wurm--totally agreed.  Some people are sheep I suppose  =)<br><br>Lunatic<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
